Custody rules
	After section 75L of each of the 1955 Acts there is inserted—
	“75MCustody rules
		The Secretary of State may make rules with respect to proceedings—
			on an application under section 75C of this Act;
			under section 75F(1) of this Act;
			on a review under section 75G(1) of this Act.
		Rules under this section may in particular make provision with respect to—
			arrangements preliminary to the proceedings;
			the representation of the person to whom the proceedings relate;
			the admissibility of evidence;
			procuring the attendance of witnesses;
			the immunities and privileges of witnesses;
			the administration of oaths;
			circumstances in which a review under section 75G(1) of this Act may becarried out without a hearing;
			the use for the purposes of the proceedings of live television links orsimilar arrangements, including the use of such a link or other arrangement asa means of satisfying the requirement of section 75C(2)(b), 75F(1) or75K(7)(b) or (8)(b) of this Act for a person to be brought before a judicialofficer or judge advocate;
			the appointment of persons to discharge administrative functions under therules.
		Rules under this section shall be made by statutory instrument subject toannulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House of Parliament.”
		After section 47M of the 1957 Act there is inserted—
	“47NCustody rules
		The Secretary of State may make rules with respect to proceedings—
			on an application under section 47D of this Act;
			under section 47G(1) of this Act;
			on a review under section 47H(1) of this Act.
		Rules under this section may in particular make provision with respect to—
			arrangements preliminary to the proceedings;
			the representation of the person to whom the proceedings relate;
			the admissibility of evidence;
			procuring the attendance of witnesses;
			the immunities and privileges of witnesses;
			the administration of oaths;
			circumstances in which a review under section 47H(1) of this Act may becarried out without a hearing;
			the use for the purposes of the proceedings of live television links orsimilar arrangements, including the use of such a link or other arrangement asa means of satisfying the requirement of section 47D(2)(b), 47G(1) or47L(7)(b) or (8)(b) of this Act for a person to be brought before a judicialofficer or judge advocate;
			the appointment of persons to discharge administrative functions under therules.
		Rules under this section shall be made by statutory instrument subject toannulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House of Parliament.”

Rules 
	After section 83ZH of each of the 1955 Acts there is inserted—
	“83ZJRules of summary appeal court
		The Secretary of State may make rules for the purpose of regulating thepractice and procedure to be followed in the summary appeal court.
		Rules under this section may, in particular, make provision—
			as to the practice and procedure of the court in exercising functionspreliminary to or incidental to the hearing of appeals under section 83ZE ofthis Act;
			as to the bringing and abandonment of appeals;
			as to the procedure for applying for leave under section 83ZE(2) or (3) ofthis Act;
			as to the procedure for applying for leave, or making a reference, undersection 115(5A) or (5B) of this Act;
			as to consultation by the court administration officer with the JudgeAdvocate General before specifying where the court is to sit;
			as to circumstances in which the jurisdiction of the court may be exercisedby a judge advocate appointed under section 83ZB of this Act sitting alone;
			enabling an uncontested appeal to be determined without a hearing;
			as to the convening and constitution of the court to hear any appeal;
			as to circumstances in which officers otherwise qualified under section83ZC of this Act are ineligible to hear particular appeals;
			enabling the appellant to object to members of the court;
			as to the representation of the appellant on the hearing of appeals undersection 83ZE of this Act and at any preliminary proceedings;
			as to the admissibility of evidence;
			as to the rehearing of an appeal where any member of the court originallyconstituted to hear it has been unable to continue hearing the appeal;
			as to procuring the attendance of witnesses at the hearing of appeals andat any preliminary proceedings;
			as to the administration of oaths;
			as to the recording of the proceedings of the court and custody of recordsof the proceedings;
			as to making copies of the records of proceedings available and as to thefees payable for such copies;
			as to the procedure for applying to have a case stated under section83ZH(2) of this Act.
		Rules under this section may provide for any enactment which relates to thepractice or procedure of courts-martial or to the admissibility of evidence incourts-martial to apply in relation to the court with such modifications asmay be specified.
		Rules under this section shall be made by statutory instrument subject toannulment in pursuance of a resolution of either House of Parliament.”
		After section 52FN of the 1957 Act there is inserted—
	“52FPRules of summary appeal court
		The Secretary of State may make rules for the purpose of regulating thepractice and procedure to be followed in the summary appeal court.
		Rules under this section may, in particular, make provision—
			as to the practice and procedure of the court in exercising functionspreliminary to or incidental to the hearing of appeals under section 52FK ofthis Act;
			as to the bringing and abandonment of appeals;
